I actually think this is one of the healthiest mindsets you can have as a founder.

You’re describing what I’d call the Ideal → MVP → Scale progression.

Most startups make one of two mistakes:

* Dream trap: They try to launch the perfect product, spend too much, run out of money, and never get to market.
* Cheap trap: They launch something that doesn’t represent the vision, and customers never see why it should exist.

The goal is to launch the smallest version that still delivers the core promise.

⸻

The Wild Hawg Ladder

Think of it like climbing a tree instead of trying to teleport to the top.

Version 1 (Launch)

Goal: Prove people want Wild Hawg.

* Great tasting gummies
* Effective energy
* Stock pouch or stock tube
* AI-assisted branding refined by a designer
* Shopify website
* Social media content
* Sell direct-to-consumer
* Learn everything

Budget: lowest practical.

Mission:

Validate demand.

⸻

Version 2 (Product-Market Fit)

Now people are buying again.

Upgrade:

* Better graphics
* Matte packaging
* Better flavors
* Better ingredients if needed
* Faster fulfillment
* Subscription program
* Influencer partnerships

Mission:

Increase repeat purchases.

⸻

Version 3 (Brand)

Now Wild Hawg starts becoming recognizable.

Invest in:

* Custom molded tube if it proves worthwhile
* Embossed lid
* Premium finishes
* Multiple flavors
* Hunting edition
* Golf edition
* Workday edition

Mission:

Become memorable.

⸻

Version 4 (Scale)

Retail.

Bass Pro.

Cabela’s.

Convenience stores.

Amazon.

Truck stops.

Mission:

Be available everywhere your customer already shops.

⸻

